04094nam a22004815i 9780226460079DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264600797 a10.7208/97802264600792doi  a(DE-B1597)524041  a(OCoLC)988326221  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aE768b.T47 2018 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a327.7300904223  aNQ 53202rvk1 aThrontveit, Trygve, eauthor.10aPower without Victory :bWoodrow Wilson and the American Internationalist Experiment /cTrygve Throntveit. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. The Ethical Republic -- tChapter Two. Common Counsel -- tChapter Three. A Certain Blindness -- tChapter Four. Trials of Neutrality -- tChapter Five. Trojan Horsemanship -- tChapter Six. Provincials No Longer -- tChapter Seven. The Will to Believe -- tChapter Eight. The Fable of the Fourteen Points -- tChapter Nine. A Living Thing Is Born -- tConclusion. Power without Victory and the Right to Believe -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations of Names and Sources Used in the Notes -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor decades, Woodrow Wilson has been remembered as either a paternalistic liberal or reactionary conservative at home and as a naïve idealist or cynical imperialist abroad. Historians' harsh judgments of Wilson are understandable. He won two elections by promising a deliberative democratic process that would ensure justice and political empowerment for all. Yet under Wilson, Jim Crow persisted, interventions in Latin America increased, and a humiliating peace settlement was forced upon Germany. A generation after Wilson, stark inequalities and injustices still plagued the nation, myopic nationalism hindered its responsible engagement in world affairs, and a second vastly destructive global conflict threatened the survival of democracy worldwide-leaving some Americans today to wonder what, exactly, the buildings and programs bearing his name are commemorating. In Power without Victory, Trygve Throntveit argues that there is more to the story of Wilson than these sad truths. Throntveit makes the case that Wilson was not a "Wilsonian," as that term has come to be understood, but a principled pragmatist in the tradition of William James. He did not seek to stamp American-style democracy on other peoples, but to enable the gradual development of a genuinely global system of governance that would maintain justice and facilitate peaceful change-a goal that, contrary to historical tradition, the American people embraced. In this brilliant intellectual, cultural, and political history, Throntveit gives us a new vision of Wilson, as well as a model of how to think about the complex relationship between the world of ideas and the worlds of policy and diplomacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226460079423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc/cover/9780226460079.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles